<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-05-20T17:34:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-05-20T17:34:00-05:00" n="247" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d247">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 861.77/397</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Chairman of the Advisory Commission of
                                    Railway Experts to Russia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SJF1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Stevens</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Harbin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-05-21T07:00:00+08:26"><hi rend="italic">May 21,
                                            1918, 7 a.m.</hi></date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 12.40 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Chinese Eastern asking if embargo at Manchuria Station can not be
                                raised at once enough to enable it to supply their workers who are
                                repairing damaged railway west and restoring transportation. I think
                                they have a feeling that in keeping embargo the Allies are not
                                neutral towards them.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_SJF1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Stevens</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>